entry.title: Check for smaller incoming soft nav count when recording
entry.content:
From analysis queries, we see URLs that have total count of soft nav LCP

larger than total soft nav count.



Currently at the recording of soft nav metrics, we check that the

incoming soft nav is not equal to the existing one, assuming that if they

are not equal, the incoming soft nav count would be larger and we know

it's a new soft nav and we should record.



Supposedly the incoming soft nav should always be larger. But we do see

before there are cases where the incoming soft nav count is smaller and

causes check(removed since) failures.



The failures are relatively rare and are unlikely to account for a large

discrepancy as we saw. But we'd like to see this fix can mitigate the

issue.

entry.title: VRR for DelayBasedBeginFrameSource
entry.content:
This change modifies DelayBasedBeginFrameSource in order to make it

compatible with the variable refresh rate feature. By using the max

VRR interval for the BeginFrameArgs, the scheduler will utilize a

delayed presentation deadline consistent with the display's maximum

vblank extension. The OnUpdateVsyncParameters callback keeps the time

source aligned with the page flips as they occur, such that each

begin frame is issued with a delay relative to the previous one by an

interval equal to the nominal rate.



Prior to this CL, the VRR feature required the

RootCompositorFrameSinkImpl to be initialized with a

BackToBackBeginFrameSource, which prevented VRR from being toggled

after startup. This change resolves that issue by updating

DelayBasedBeginFrameSource to work with VRR.



This change should not have any impact when the VRR feature is disabled.

The DelayBasedBeginFrameSource should fallback to the nominal refresh

interval which is consistent with the preexisting behavior.

entry.title: media/gpu/test: Skip FlushMidStream on VP9 show_existing_frame vectors
entry.content:
Some VP9 test vectors (vda_smoke-vp90_2_17_show_existing_frame.vp9, run

from ChromeOS Tast) exercise the "show_existing_frame" functionality,

where "If show_existing_frame is equal to 1, then the decoder should

output a previously decoded frame..." [1].



This test case flushes carelessly in the middle of the stream, so

frames after the flush can potentially request to show a frame from

before the flush, jamming the decoder.



This CL skips the test on these specific test vectors. This was done

for the new, unlaunched V4L2StatefulVideoDecoder, but it applies to

ToT V4L2VideoDecoder/V4L2StatefulVideoDecoderBackend.



[1] "VP9 Bitstream & Decoding Process Specification - v0.6 31st March

2016", Sec 8.9 PP106.

https://storage.googleapis.com/downloads.webmproject.org/docs/vp9/vp9-bitstream-specification-v0.6-20160331-draft.pdf

entry.title: Relative color components are unitless, remove tests assuming otherwise
entry.content:
Some old spec examples combined color components (which are unitless)

with percentages and angles. Per spec, this is invalid:



https://drafts.css-houdini.org/css-typed-om-1/#numeric-typing



These examples were changed here, but remained in WPT:

https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/commit/76d3f78c62cee437735a4b9ef5726307c7020b12

https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/commit/c3de94f0d0d77246c6b23f5acea8dc7b86a71d5e



These invalid tests are removed and the valid, unitless versions that

exist inside the spec are included in color-valid-relative-color and

color-computed-relative-color instead:

https://drafts.csswg.org/css-color-5/



Since tests are being removed here, virtual/stable needs to change.



Also, the Example numbers are removed from the test file because they

appear to change often. For example, they are now different on the

publication version, which is different from the current draft, which

is different from the test. It's probably not worthwhile to keep these

in sync.

entry.title: Fix an overly aggressive DCHECKs for whitespace in custom properties.
entry.content:
ParseDeclarationValue() is responsible for handing back a string

that has neither leading nor trailing whitespace. Stripping

trailing whitespace is handled by StripTrailingWhitespaceAndComments(),

which then has a DCHECK verifying that the leading whitespace had been

stripped earlier in the process, so that we returned without either:



[no leading whitespace here]some text blabla[any trailing spaces]



However, if the result is the empty string (“some text blabla” is empty),

the test would think that the “any trailing spaces” part was actually

part of leading whitespace that it didn't strip, and thus error out.



We fix this by simply moving the check for no leading whitespace

to the end of the function, after stripping the trailing. Thus,

we care more about the invariant at the end of the function, which is

what is important.



Fixed: 1476811

entry.title: Reland "Invalidation on stylesheet changes using selector matching"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 5d12010188b8fd648efd2279956e8a6cbe20654e.

The revert has been in for ~6 hours and the tests in question still

fail on the Mac builders, so it's unlikely to be the culprit.

It also passes locally on Mac.



Original change's description:

> Invalidation on stylesheet changes using selector matching

>

> When inserting, deleting or modifying stylesheets, we need to invalidate

> style for some elements, even though the elements themselves did not

> change. Currently, we reuse the concept of InvalidationSets, which are

> mostly designed for changes to elements, for that. This can sometimes

> cause overbroad invalidations, especially if the style is written in

> a “modern” (read: less-than-ideal) fashion.

>

> We replace this by a somewhat slower but more precise and probably

> simpler system; for each candidate element in the DOM, we see if it

> matches any selectors in the old or the new rulesets (by means of

> the same bucketing logic we currently have during element rule

> collection), and if so, we mark it for style recalc. This isn't perfect;

> if we are e.g. adding a single rule to an existing stylesheet, we would

> still invalidate based on all rules in the sheet. We hope to improve

> this in a future patch, but even now, this shows significant

> improvements over most of blink_perf.css, with only a few regressions.

>

> Note that this means the experimental style invalidation information in

> devtools becomes somewhat less useful; it will no longer give reasons

> for invalidations when style sheets change. Fixing this would probably

> involve extending the protocol, although I haven't looked deeply into

> this.

entry.title: Don't add tree-scoped references to MPC
entry.content:
MatchedPropertiesCache could not re-use cache entries for shared

stylesheets across trees because tree-scoped names/references would be

resolved differently depending on tree-scope. We solved that by

including the TreeScope pointers in the hash key. However,

RemoveCachedMatchedPropertiesWithDeadEntries() would not be able to

clear out old entries from removed shadow tree if the stylesheet they

originated from still was in use in another tree-scope, leading to an

ever-growing MPC when e.g. web components were continuously added and

removed from the tree.



Instead, avoid the MPC completely if the matched properties contain

tree-scoped references.

entry.title: [ForceSigninVerifier] Ensure IdentityManger ref is freed
entry.content:
ForceSigninVerifier is owned by the ChromeSigninClient.

ForceSigninVerifier contains a reference to the IdentityManger.



IdentityManager indirectly depends on ChromeSigninClient, meaning that

we cannot add the regular DependsOn dependency, since it would create

a circular dependency between the factories.



The issue is that the IdentityManager is destroyed before the

ChromeSigninClient (order of dependency) which means ForceSigninVerifier

will hold an invalid reference to the IdentityManager.



---



The solution in this CL is to listen to the destruction of the

IdentityManager via the ShutDownNotifier service, and make it depend

on the IdentityManager.



There seems to be a bigger issue with the dependency between the

KeyedService Factories.

entry.title: iwa: Fix IWA updates if a ServiceWorker has a fetch handler
entry.content:
It is important to bypass a potentially registered Service Worker during

IWA installation and updates:

1. Our mechanism to attach the location of the to-be-installed IWA to

the WebContents via `IsolatedWebAppPendingInstallInfo` is bypassed if

a Service Worker intercepts the requests in a fetch handler, because

such requests are not tied to any particular WebContents.

2. By ignoring Service Workers, we also prevent an IWA from maliciously

or accidentally tampering with our generated install page.



As part of this fix, I also updated the `WebAppUrlLoader` fakes to

overwrite the more generic `LoadUrl` method.

entry.title: pip-pinch: Handle PiP pinch gesture started by client
entry.content:
This commit allows the client to initiate the pinch gesture.

When the target of a drag event is a client, ToplevelWindowEventHandler

does not initiate the drag and instead waits for the client to initiate

it. We have implemented the same feature to the pinch gesture. To

achieve this, 2 modifications were needed to be made:



1. AttemptToStartDrag, when called from client, now dispatches

AttemptToStartDrag or AttemptToStartPinch depending on the last gesture

recorded by ToplevelWindowEventHandler.



2. AttemptToStartPinch now transfers events from ExoSurface to

ExoShellSurface and updates gesture_target_ when called from the client.
